Introduction

I am interested in how race and the level of education affects the income of people that have gained US citizenship through the process of naturalization. The variables I have selected to investigate this interdependency are age, income, race, employment status, level of education, year of entry, and period of citizenship. I calculated the period of citizenship as the difference between the year of entry and the year when the person acquired the citizenship.

I retrieved these variables from the 2018 ACS1 dataset for the state of California. My sample population is citizens over 18 years old that have attained their citizenship by naturalization, with a total of 31246 observations. I chose these variables because I believe that race, in tandem with period of citizenship, affect an individual’s income.

Data

The variables I selected to answer my research question are as follows: 1. Age (continuous variable) 2. Income (continuous variable) 3. Race (categorical variable) 4. Employment status (categorical variable) 5. Level of education (categorical variable) 6. Year of entry (continuous variable) 7. Period of citizenship (continuous variable)

These variables are retrieved from the 2018 ACS1 dataset for California. The following table presents the sample mean, median, standard deviation, interquartile range, and population mean for the continuous variables, with a 95% confidence interval. The distribution for each of the continuous variables is visualized on Figure 1, 2 and 3.

In the following tables, I observe the shares of the categorical variables, namely race, employment, and level of education.

Regression models

I will run regression models, choosing the following variables: 1. Dependent: Income. 2. Independent: Race, employment, level of education and period of citizenship.

The preferred regression model has an interaction term for education, as opposed to the interaction term of employment for the initial model.

Results

After looking at the separate correlation tests, Anova and chi-squared tests, I ran two linear regression models. The adjusted R-squared value for the preferred model is 0.15, a 1% improve from the initial model. This indicates that there is a statistically significant relationship between the level of education race, and income in the dataset of people that gained citizenship through naturalization. The preferred model indicates that: 1. People belong to other race (not specified on the list) make on average 5205$ less than white people (p-value of 2e-17). 2. Employed people make 31416$ more than people that are unemployed (p-value of 2.2e-17). 3. People that have a bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 11198$ more than people that have a high school degree. 4. People that are employed and have a Bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 42663$ more than people that are unemployed and have a high school degree (p-value 2.2e-17). 5. Black people that have a Bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 15212$ less than white people with a Bachelor’s degree, statistical significance indicated by a p-value of 0.01. 6. People that belong to other race, not specified by the previous categories, and have a Bachelor’s degree or higher, make on average 31033$ less.

Discussion

I ran a linear regression to ask the research question How do race and the level of education affect the income of people that have gained US citizenship through the process of naturalization? Does race affect the income? The dependant variable was income, and the independent variables were race, employment, level of education and period of citizenship. The adjusted R-squared value of the preferred model is 0.15, meaning this model predicts circa 15% of variations in income in this dataset.

Race

The findings clearly state that there is a statistical significance between race and income for people that have gained their citizenship by process of naturalization. Initially, people that belong to other race (not specified on the list) make on average 5205 dollars less than white people (p-value of 2e-17). This finding should not be taken at face value, and should be investigated further by adding more race categories to the model. In addition, people that belong to other race, not specified by the previous categories, and have a Bachelor’s degree or higher, make on average 31033$ less (p-value of 2e-17). The most striking finding was that Black people that have a Bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 15212$ less than white people with a Bachelor’s degree, statistical significance indicated by a p-value of 0.01.

Level of education

As for the level of education, it was not surprising to see that people that have a bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 11198 dollars more than people that have a high school degree. In addition, people that are employed and have a Bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 42663$ more than people that are unemployed and have a high school degree (p-value 2.2e-17). However, in order to dilute meaningful data about education, I encourage future researchers to do a qualitative analysis, as the level of education is (thankfully) not following a global standard, and therefore has multiple layers and nuances that contribute to work force integration.

Limitations of the research

Period of Citizenship ought not be taken at a face value. Building on a cross-sectional study of regulations and policies governing the process of naturalization, this would be a variable that would provide meaning to Period of Citizenship. This would imply that the year of naturalization, combined with citizenship policies, would be more contextualized and meaningful. One ought to take into account the accreditation of educational institutions from around the world, and the extent they are recognized from states; we have witnessed stories of immigrants having a successful career, academic or otherwise, in their homecountries, that could not be equivalented to US, strong-arming them towards low-income wages, more reliance on family and extended family structures as a safety net, or starting their academic journey from the start again. Finally, I would encourage future researchers to run a zero-inflated binomial model, or a Poisson model, due to the fact that income has a disproportionate number of observations equal to zero. This rendered logging income futile, and running any of these models was simply beyond the scope of this project.

Conclusion

This research aims to explore the relationship between race, level of education and income for people that have gained US citizenship through the process of naturalization. The dataset consists of 31246 observations from 2018 ACS1 for the state of California, for people over 18 years old that have attained citizenship through the process of naturalization. I hypothesize that race, and level of education, in tandem with period of citizenship (as a secondary variable) affect an individual’s income. My analysis consists of a linear regression model that predicts 15% of variations in income, consisting of indenpendent variables for race, employment, level of education and period of citizenship and an interaction term for education. The results indicate that there is a statistical significance between race and income, more strikingly that Black people that have a Bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 15212 dollars less than white people with a Bachelor’s degree (p-value of 0.01). Furthermore, there is a statistically significant relationship between the level of education, and a bachelor’s degree or higher make on average 11198 dollars more than people that have a high school degree. However, recognizing the boundaries of this is primordially a cry for contextualization: acquiring citizenship is highly governed by foreign regulations and policies, meaning that the period of citizenship in and of itself should not be taken at face value. Additionally, varying accreditation of different educational institutions from around the world plays a major role for the work force integration of people that have gained their citizenship by process of naturalization, perhaps making them more vulnerable and strong-arming them towards low-paying jobs, due to the fact that the costs of starting an undergraduate or graduate degree is insupportable.
